Note: ===================================================================
Note: SOLIDITY SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for Solidity smart contract language. Handles
Note: contract validation, security analysis, gas optimization, type
Note: checking, and Ethereum Virtual Machine compatibility verification.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/solidity/solidity_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/solidity/solidity_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Aggregates every cross-reference table the Solidity semantic phase
needs. Solidity is structurally complex: contracts inherit (with C3
linearisation), state variables and functions live qualified by
contract name, and security/gas analysis must walk every function
again after declaration collection. Storing all registries on a
single analyzer object lets each pass be a simple top-level Process
call rather than threading dictionaries through every function.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
26 i64-sized fields, occupying 208 bytes total at offsets 0..200.
Declaration registries (contracts/interfaces/libraries/structs/
enums/state_variables/functions/modifiers/events/errors) are
Dictionaries keyed by qualified name. imports/pragma_directives are
Lists. inheritance_graph maps contract_name -> List of parents.
function_signatures and state_mutability and visibility_modifiers
map qualified_name -> attribute. security_issues, gas_warnings,
reentrancy_risks, overflow_risks, access_control_issues,
validation_errors, validation_warnings are Lists of message strings.
compiler_version stores the pragma value pointer; error_message and
has_error are the fatal-error flag/pointer pair.
@End Implementation
Type called "SoliditySemanticAnalyzer":
    contracts as Integer
    interfaces as Integer
    libraries as Integer
    structs as Integer
    enums as Integer
    state_variables as Integer
    functions as Integer
    modifiers as Integer
    events as Integer
    errors as Integer
    imports as Integer
    inheritance_graph as Integer
    function_signatures as Integer
    state_mutability as Integer
    visibility_modifiers as Integer
    security_issues as Integer
    gas_warnings as Integer
    reentrancy_risks as Integer
    overflow_risks as Integer
    access_control_issues as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    compiler_version as Integer
    pragma_directives as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Zero-arg factory because the Solidity analyzer is a per-translation-unit
worker: each call mints a fresh 208-byte record so concurrent translations
cannot collide on shared registries, and partial-failure cleanup is just a
single deallocate. Returning 0 on the Layout.allocate failure path (instead
of aborting) keeps the analyzer construction non-fatal — the driver decides
how to react to OOM.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 208-byte block matching the SoliditySemanticAnalyzer slot map
(26 i64 slots, offsets 0..200). Creates one Dict/List per registry slot
(0..168), then initialises pragma_directives at 184. Slot 176
(compiler_version), 192 (error_message), and 200 (has_error) are written
as 0 — they are populated lazily by collect_solidity_pragmas and
set_solidity_semantic_error. Slot order in memory_set_int64 calls MUST
match the Type declaration above; any reordering corrupts every accessor.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_solidity_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create Solidity semantic analyzer for smart contract validation

    Let analyzer_size be 208
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let contracts be proc create from Dict
    Let interfaces be proc create from Dict
    Let libraries be proc create from Dict
    Let structs be proc create from Dict
    Let enums be proc create from Dict
    Let state_variables be proc create from Dict
    Let functions be proc create from Dict
    Let modifiers be proc create from Dict
    Let events be proc create from Dict
    Let errors be proc create from Dict
    Let imports be proc create from List
    Let inheritance_graph be proc create from Dict
    Let function_signatures be proc create from Dict
    Let state_mutability be proc create from Dict
    Let visibility_modifiers be proc create from Dict
    Let security_issues be proc create from List
    Let gas_warnings be proc create from List
    Let reentrancy_risks be proc create from List
    Let overflow_risks be proc create from List
    Let access_control_issues be proc create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc create from List
    Let pragma_directives be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, contracts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, interfaces
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, libraries
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, structs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, enums
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, state_variables
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, modifiers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, events
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, imports
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, inheritance_graph
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, function_signatures
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, state_mutability
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, visibility_modifiers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, security_issues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, gas_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136, reentrancy_risks
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144, overflow_risks
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152, access_control_issues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176, 0  Note: compiler_version
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184, pragma_directives
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200, 0  Note: has_error

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Null-guards analyzer and solidity_ast. On null AST, calls
set_solidity_semantic_error with "Null Solidity AST" and returns 0.
Otherwise runs six pipeline phases in order:
  1. collect_solidity_pragmas - pragmas and imports
  2. collect_solidity_declarations - all contracts/libs/interfaces
  3. validate_solidity_contracts - inheritance and overrides
  4. analyze_solidity_security - reentrancy/overflow/access control
  5. analyze_solidity_gas_usage - gas optimisation advisories
  6. validate_solidity_types - type compatibility
Finally checks has_error @200 - returns 0 if set, otherwise 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_solidity_contract" takes analyzer as Integer, solidity_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on Solidity contract

    @Reasoning:
    Comprehensive analysis including contract validation, security analysis,
    gas optimization, type checking, inheritance validation, and Ethereum
    Virtual Machine compatibility verification for secure smart contracts.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    Multi-phase analysis: collect declarations, validate contracts, analyze
    security, check gas usage, validate inheritance, and enforce Solidity
    conventions for secure and optimized smart contracts.
    @End Implementation

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If solidity_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_solidity_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null Solidity AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Collect pragma directives and imports
    proc collect_solidity_pragmas with analyzer, solidity_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Collect contract declarations and definitions
    proc collect_solidity_declarations with analyzer, solidity_ast

    Note: Phase 3: Validate contract structure and inheritance
    proc validate_solidity_contracts from analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Perform security analysis
    proc analyze_solidity_security from analyzer

    Note: Phase 5: Analyze gas usage and optimization
    proc analyze_solidity_gas_usage from analyzer

    Note: Phase 6: Validate type compatibility and function signatures
    proc validate_solidity_types from analyzer

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PRAGMA AND IMPORT COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Two parallel sweeps on the AST:
  Pragmas: get_solidity_pragma_statements. For each, appends to the
    pragma_directives list @184 and calls
    check_solidity_version_pragma.
  Imports: get_solidity_import_statements. For each, appends to the
    imports list @80 and calls validate_solidity_import.
Both null-check the AST accessor results because pragmas and
imports are optional in a Solidity source file.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_solidity_pragmas" takes analyzer as Integer, solidity_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect pragma directives and import statements

    @Reasoning:
    Collect compiler version requirements, experimental features, and
    import statements for dependency analysis and version compatibility
    checking according to Solidity pragma specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    Let pragma_statements be proc get_solidity_pragma_statements from solidity_ast
    If pragma_statements is not equal to 0:
        Let pragma_directives be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184
        Let pragma_count be proc size from List with pragma_statements
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than pragma_count:
            Let pragma_stmt be proc get from List with pragma_statements, i
            proc add from List with pragma_directives, pragma_stmt

            Note: Check for compiler version pragma
            proc check_solidity_version_pragma with analyzer, pragma_stmt

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let import_statements be proc get_solidity_import_statements from solidity_ast
    If import_statements is not equal to 0:
        Let imports be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
        Let import_count be proc size from List with import_statements
        Set i to 0

        While i is less than import_count:
            Let import_stmt be proc get from List with import_statements, i
            proc add from List with imports, import_stmt

            Note: Validate import path and dependencies
            proc validate_solidity_import with analyzer, import_stmt

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads pragma_type and pragma_value from the AST. Calls string_equals
to test if pragma_type is "solidity". If yes, stores pragma_value
into analyzer @176 (the compiler_version field) and calls
validate_solidity_version_format. Non-solidity pragmas (e.g.
"experimental") are silently ignored at this layer.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_solidity_version_pragma" takes analyzer as Integer, pragma_stmt as Integer:
    Note: Check Solidity compiler version pragma

    @Reasoning:
    Validate pragma solidity version specification, check for compatible
    version ranges, and ensure version requirements are appropriate for
    features used in the contract.
    @End Reasoning

    Let pragma_type be proc get_solidity_pragma_type from pragma_stmt
    Let pragma_value be proc get_solidity_pragma_value from pragma_stmt

    Let is_solidity_pragma be proc string_equals from StringCore with pragma_type, "solidity"
    If is_solidity_pragma is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176, pragma_value

        Note: Validate version format
        proc validate_solidity_version_format with analyzer, pragma_value
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DECLARATION COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Reads the contract_definitions list from the AST. Iterates each
definition, reading its contract_type. Match on the type string:
"contract" -> collect_solidity_contract,
"interface" -> collect_solidity_interface,
"library" -> collect_solidity_library,
otherwise registers a warning "Unknown contract type: <type>" via
add_solidity_validation_warning.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_solidity_declarations" takes analyzer as Integer, solidity_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect all Solidity contract declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Collect contracts, interfaces, libraries, structs, enums, and other
    declarations to build comprehensive registries for cross-reference
    validation and inheritance analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let contract_definitions be proc get_solidity_contract_definitions from solidity_ast
    Let definition_count be proc size from List with contract_definitions
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than definition_count:
        Let contract_def be proc get from List with contract_definitions, i
        Let contract_type be proc get_solidity_contract_type from contract_def

        Match contract_type:
            When "contract":
                proc collect_solidity_contract with analyzer, contract_def
            When "interface":
                proc collect_solidity_interface with analyzer, contract_def
            When "library":
                proc collect_solidity_library with analyzer, contract_def
            Otherwise:
                Let warning be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Unknown contract type: ", contract_type
                proc add_solidity_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End Match

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads contract_name from the AST node. Looks up contracts_registry
@0. If the name is already present, registers a "Duplicate contract
definition" error and returns. Otherwise sets the dictionary entry
and runs five collection sub-passes: inheritance, state variables,
functions, modifiers, events/errors. Each sub-pass populates the
corresponding analyzer-level registries with qualified names.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_solidity_contract" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract definition

    @Reasoning:
    Register contract with inheritance, state variables, functions, modifiers,
    events, and errors for comprehensive contract analysis and security
    validation. Contracts are the primary executable units in Solidity.
    @End Reasoning

    Let contract_name be proc get_solidity_contract_name from contract_def
    Let contracts_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Note: Check for duplicate contract
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with contracts_registry, contract_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Duplicate contract definition: ", contract_name
        proc add_solidity_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    proc set from Dict with contracts_registry, contract_name, contract_def

    Note: Collect contract inheritance
    proc collect_contract_inheritance with analyzer, contract_name, contract_def

    Note: Collect contract state variables
    proc collect_contract_state_variables with analyzer, contract_name, contract_def

    Note: Collect contract functions
    proc collect_contract_functions with analyzer, contract_name, contract_def

    Note: Collect contract modifiers
    proc collect_contract_modifiers with analyzer, contract_name, contract_def

    Note: Collect contract events and errors
    proc collect_contract_events_errors with analyzer, contract_name, contract_def
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_solidity_contract_inheritance on contract_def. If the
inheritance list is null (contract declared no parents), returns.
Otherwise reads inheritance_graph @88 and sets contract_name ->
inheritance_list on the dictionary. Then calls
validate_inheritance_hierarchy for early sanity checks (each parent
name resolves to a known contract).
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_contract_inheritance" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract inheritance relationships

    @Reasoning:
    Register inheritance relationships for linearization validation, function
    override checking, and proper inheritance graph construction according
    to Solidity inheritance rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let inheritance_list be proc get_solidity_contract_inheritance from contract_def
    If inheritance_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let inheritance_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    proc set from Dict with inheritance_graph, contract_name, inheritance_list

    Note: Validate inheritance hierarchy
    proc validate_inheritance_hierarchy with analyzer, contract_name, inheritance_list
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_solidity_contract_state_variables. If null returns. Reads
state_variables @40, visibility_modifiers @112, state_mutability
@104. Iterates each state_var: extracts var_name, var_type,
var_visibility, var_mutability via parser accessors. Builds
qualified_var_name as "ContractName.varName" via two string_concat
calls. Sets the dictionary entries on all three registries. Then
calls validate_state_variable_declaration for the syntactic checks.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_contract_state_variables" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract state variable declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register state variables with types, visibility, mutability, and initial
    values for storage analysis, gas optimization, and security validation.
    State variables define contract storage layout.
    @End Reasoning

    Let state_vars_list be proc get_solidity_contract_state_variables from contract_def
    If state_vars_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let state_variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let visibility_modifiers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    Let state_mutability be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let var_count be proc size from List with state_vars_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than var_count:
        Let state_var be proc get from List with state_vars_list, i
        Let var_name be proc get_solidity_state_variable_name from state_var
        Let var_type be proc get_solidity_state_variable_type from state_var
        Let var_visibility be proc get_solidity_state_variable_visibility from state_var
        Let var_mutability be proc get_solidity_state_variable_mutability from state_var

        Let qualified_var_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with contract_name, "."
        Set qualified_var_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with qualified_var_name, var_name

        proc set from Dict with state_variables, qualified_var_name, state_var
        proc set from Dict with visibility_modifiers, qualified_var_name, var_visibility
        proc set from Dict with state_mutability, qualified_var_name, var_mutability

        Note: Validate state variable declaration
        proc validate_state_variable_declaration with analyzer, contract_name, state_var

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_solidity_contract_functions. If null returns. Reads four
registries: functions_registry @48, function_signatures @96,
visibility_modifiers @112, state_mutability @104. Iterates each
function_def, calling parser accessors to extract func_name,
func_signature, func_visibility, func_mutability. Builds
qualified_func_name as "ContractName.funcName". Sets all four
registries on that key. Calls validate_function_declaration for
the per-function syntactic checks.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_contract_functions" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract function declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register functions with signatures, visibility, mutability, modifiers,
    and implementation for function override validation, gas analysis,
    and security checking. Functions define contract behavior.
    @End Reasoning

    Let functions_list be proc get_solidity_contract_functions from contract_def
    If functions_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let function_signatures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let visibility_modifiers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    Let state_mutability be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let func_count be proc size from List with functions_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let function_def be proc get from List with functions_list, i
        Let func_name be proc get_solidity_function_name from function_def
        Let func_signature be proc get_solidity_function_signature from function_def
        Let func_visibility be proc get_solidity_function_visibility from function_def
        Let func_mutability be proc get_solidity_function_state_mutability from function_def

        Let qualified_func_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with contract_name, "."
        Set qualified_func_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with qualified_func_name, func_name

        proc set from Dict with functions_registry, qualified_func_name, function_def
        proc set from Dict with function_signatures, qualified_func_name, func_signature
        proc set from Dict with visibility_modifiers, qualified_func_name, func_visibility
        proc set from Dict with state_mutability, qualified_func_name, func_mutability

        Note: Validate function declaration
        proc validate_function_declaration with analyzer, contract_name, function_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_solidity_contract_modifiers. If null returns. Reads
modifiers_registry @56. Iterates each modifier_def, calls
get_solidity_modifier_name, builds qualified_modifier_name as
"ContractName.modifierName" via string_concat, and sets that key on
the dictionary. Calls validate_modifier_declaration for per-modifier
checks.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_contract_modifiers" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract modifier declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register modifiers for access control analysis and security validation.
    Modifiers define reusable access control and validation logic for
    functions in Solidity contracts.
    @End Reasoning

    Let modifiers_list be proc get_solidity_contract_modifiers from contract_def
    If modifiers_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let modifiers_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let modifier_count be proc size from List with modifiers_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than modifier_count:
        Let modifier_def be proc get from List with modifiers_list, i
        Let modifier_name be proc get_solidity_modifier_name from modifier_def

        Let qualified_modifier_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with contract_name, "."
        Set qualified_modifier_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with qualified_modifier_name, modifier_name

        proc set from Dict with modifiers_registry, qualified_modifier_name, modifier_def

        Note: Validate modifier declaration
        proc validate_modifier_declaration with analyzer, contract_name, modifier_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Two separate sub-loops sharing the same skeleton:
  Events: get_solidity_contract_events. If non-null, reads events
    registry @64. Iterates each event_def, gets its event_name,
    builds "ContractName.EventName" via string concat, and sets the
    dictionary entry.
  Errors: get_solidity_contract_errors. If non-null, reads errors
    registry @72. Same iteration pattern producing
    "ContractName.ErrorName" keys.
Both null-check the list pointers because events and errors are
optional in a contract definition.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_contract_events_errors" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, contract_def as Integer:
    Note: Collect contract events and error declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register events and custom errors for proper usage validation and
    gas analysis. Events provide logging functionality while custom errors
    provide gas-efficient error handling in Solidity.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Collect events
    Let events_list be proc get_solidity_contract_events from contract_def
    If events_list is not equal to 0:
        Let events_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
        Let event_count be proc size from List with events_list
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than event_count:
            Let event_def be proc get from List with events_list, i
            Let event_name be proc get_solidity_event_name from event_def

            Let qualified_event_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with contract_name, "."
            Set qualified_event_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with qualified_event_name, event_name

            proc set from Dict with events_registry, qualified_event_name, event_def

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Collect custom errors
    Let errors_list be proc get_solidity_contract_errors from contract_def
    If errors_list is not equal to 0:
        Let errors_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
        Let error_count be proc size from List with errors_list
        Set i to 0

        While i is less than error_count:
            Let error_def be proc get from List with errors_list, i
            Let error_name be proc get_solidity_error_name from error_def

            Let qualified_error_name be proc string_concat from StringCore with contract_name, "."
            Set qualified_error_name to proc string_concat from StringCore with qualified_error_name, error_name

            proc set from Dict with errors_registry, qualified_error_name, error_def

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CONTRACT VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four validation sub-passes:
  1. validate_inheritance_linearization - C3 linearization check
  2. validate_function_overrides - override signature compatibility
  3. validate_interface_implementations - contracts must implement all
     declared interface methods
  4. check_contract_naming_conventions - Solidity naming style
Each sub-pass registers any failures via add_solidity_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_solidity_contracts" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate contract structure and inheritance

    @Reasoning:
    Validate contract inheritance linearization, function override consistency,
    interface implementation, and contract structure according to Solidity
    contract and inheritance specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_inheritance_linearization from analyzer
    proc validate_function_overrides from analyzer
    proc validate_interface_implementations from analyzer
    proc check_contract_naming_conventions from analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads inheritance_graph @88. Lists its keys (one per contract that
declared parents). For each contract_name, calls
validate_contract_linearization which runs the per-contract C3 check.
Contracts with no recorded parents are not in the graph and so do
not enter this loop - which is correct because a contract with no
parents has trivial linearisation.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_inheritance_linearization" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate contract inheritance linearization (C3 linearization)

    @Reasoning:
    Validate inheritance follows C3 linearization rules, detect diamond
    inheritance issues, and ensure proper method resolution order
    according to Solidity inheritance specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    Let inheritance_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let contract_names be proc keys from Dict with inheritance_graph
    Let contract_count be proc size from List with contract_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than contract_count:
        Let contract_name be proc get from List with contract_names, i
        proc validate_contract_linearization with analyzer, contract_name
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Looks up parent_list in inheritance_graph @88 for contract_name. If
non-null, allocates two scratch Lists (visited and visiting) and
calls detect_circular_inheritance with the contract_name as the
starting node. Then calls compute_linearization_order which
implements the C3 algorithm proper. The visited/visiting separation
matches the standard DFS cycle-detection idiom: a node in 'visiting'
that is re-entered is a cycle, a node already in 'visited' is just
a shared ancestor.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_contract_linearization" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer:
    Note: Validate specific contract's inheritance linearization

    @Reasoning:
    Check contract inheritance hierarchy follows valid linearization order,
    detect circular inheritance, and validate override resolution order
    matches Solidity inheritance semantics.
    @End Reasoning

    Let inheritance_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let parent_list be proc get from Dict with inheritance_graph, contract_name

    If parent_list is not equal to 0:
        Note: Check for circular inheritance
        Let visited be proc create from List
        Let visiting be proc create from List
        proc detect_circular_inheritance with analyzer, contract_name, visited, visiting

        Note: Validate linearization order
        proc compute_linearization_order with analyzer, contract_name, parent_list
    End If
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads contracts_registry @0 and iterates each contract by name.
For each contract, delegates to validate_contract_function_overrides
which inspects functions marked virtual/override and verifies that
the override matches the virtual's signature, visibility, and
state mutability.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_function_overrides" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate function override specifications

    @Reasoning:
    Check function overrides have compatible signatures, proper override
    keywords, visibility consistency, and state mutability compatibility
    according to Solidity function override rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let contracts_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let contract_names be proc keys from Dict with contracts_registry
    Let contract_count be proc size from List with contract_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than contract_count:
        Let contract_name be proc get from List with contract_names, i
        proc validate_contract_function_overrides with analyzer, contract_name
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SECURITY ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls five security sub-passes:
  1. detect_reentrancy_vulnerabilities
  2. check_integer_overflow_underflow
  3. analyze_access_control
  4. check_unchecked_external_calls
  5. validate_input_validation
Each populates its corresponding list on the analyzer
(reentrancy_risks, overflow_risks, access_control_issues, etc.).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_solidity_security" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Perform comprehensive security analysis

    @Reasoning:
    Analyze smart contract security including reentrancy vulnerabilities,
    integer overflow/underflow, access control issues, and other common
    smart contract security patterns and anti-patterns.
    @End Reasoning

    proc detect_reentrancy_vulnerabilities from analyzer
    proc check_integer_overflow_underflow from analyzer
    proc analyze_access_control from analyzer
    proc check_unchecked_external_calls from analyzer
    proc validate_input_validation from analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads functions_registry @48 and reentrancy_risks @136. Iterates the
function names. For each, looks up the function_def and calls
analyze_function_reentrancy_risk to do the per-function analysis.
This is a flat sweep - cross-function call graph analysis is the
job of a later, deeper pass that consumes the per-function flags
this populates.
@End Implementation
Process called "detect_reentrancy_vulnerabilities" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Detect reentrancy attack vulnerabilities

    @Reasoning:
    Identify functions that make external calls before updating state,
    check for proper reentrancy guards, and detect patterns that could
    lead to reentrancy attacks in smart contracts.
    @End Reasoning

    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let reentrancy_risks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let function_names be proc keys from Dict with functions_registry
    Let func_count be proc size from List with function_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let function_name be proc get from List with function_names, i
        Let function_def be proc get from Dict with functions_registry, function_name

        proc analyze_function_reentrancy_risk with analyzer, function_name, function_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads function_body via the parser accessor. If null returns early.
Calls contains_external_calls and contains_state_changes. Only when
BOTH are true does it then check
external_calls_before_state_changes; if that returns 1, builds a
"Potential reentrancy vulnerability in function: <name>" message
and appends to reentrancy_risks @136.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Detects the classic checks-effects-interactions violation. Does NOT
detect reentrancy guards (modifier nonReentrant) - that suppression
logic lives in the modifier-aware pass that consumes this advisory.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_function_reentrancy_risk" takes analyzer as Integer, function_name as Integer, function_def as Integer:
    Note: Analyze individual function for reentrancy risk

    @Reasoning:
    Check function for external calls followed by state changes, absence
    of reentrancy guards, and other patterns that indicate potential
    reentrancy vulnerabilities.
    @End Reasoning

    Let function_body be proc get_solidity_function_body from function_def
    If function_body is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let has_external_calls be proc contains_external_calls from function_body
    Let has_state_changes be proc contains_state_changes from function_body

    If has_external_calls is equal to 1 and has_state_changes is equal to 1:
        Note: Check order of external calls vs state changes
        Let call_before_state be proc external_calls_before_state_changes from function_body

        If call_before_state is equal to 1:
            Let reentrancy_risks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
            Let risk_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Potential reentrancy vulnerability in function: ", function_name
            proc add from List with reentrancy_risks, risk_msg
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads functions_registry @48 and overflow_risks @144. Lists function
names and iterates. For each function_def, calls
analyze_function_arithmetic_safety which inspects the body for
arithmetic in unchecked { } blocks (which skip Solidity 0.8+ default
checks), pre-0.8 contracts without SafeMath, and unbounded integer
casts that could truncate.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_integer_overflow_underflow" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check for integer overflow/underflow vulnerabilities

    @Reasoning:
    Identify arithmetic operations that could overflow or underflow,
    check for proper SafeMath usage or Solidity 0.8+ built-in checks,
    and detect unchecked arithmetic blocks.
    @End Reasoning

    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let overflow_risks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    Let function_names be proc keys from Dict with functions_registry
    Let func_count be proc size from List with function_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let function_name be proc get from List with function_names, i
        Let function_def be proc get from Dict with functions_registry, function_name

        proc analyze_function_arithmetic_safety with analyzer, function_name, function_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads functions_registry @48 and access_control_issues @152. Lists
function names and iterates. For each function_def, calls
analyze_function_access_control which checks for missing modifiers
on privileged operations, ownership pattern correctness, and
delegatecall/selfdestruct guards.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Operates on already-parsed AST nodes. No untrusted byte parsing
here. The downstream analyze_function_access_control is the actual
security-detection logic.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_access_control" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze access control patterns and vulnerabilities

    @Reasoning:
    Check proper use of access control modifiers, validate owner patterns,
    identify functions missing access controls, and detect privilege
    escalation vulnerabilities in smart contracts.
    @End Reasoning

    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let access_control_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152
    Let function_names be proc keys from Dict with functions_registry
    Let func_count be proc size from List with function_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let function_name be proc get from List with function_names, i
        Let function_def be proc get from Dict with functions_registry, function_name

        proc analyze_function_access_control with analyzer, function_name, function_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: GAS ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four gas sub-passes:
  1. analyze_storage_gas_usage - storage layout efficiency
  2. check_loop_gas_limits - loop bound and complexity issues
  3. identify_gas_optimizations - general optimisation patterns
  4. validate_gas_estimates - check explicit gas hints are sensible
Each appends advisories to gas_warnings.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_solidity_gas_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze gas usage and optimization opportunities

    @Reasoning:
    Analyze gas consumption patterns, identify optimization opportunities,
    detect gas limit issues, and provide recommendations for gas-efficient
    smart contract implementation.
    @End Reasoning

    proc analyze_storage_gas_usage from analyzer
    proc check_loop_gas_limits from analyzer
    proc identify_gas_optimizations from analyzer
    proc validate_gas_estimates from analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads state_variables @40 and gas_warnings list @128. Iterates the
qualified variable names. For each state_var, calls
analyze_storage_variable_gas which checks for packable layout (multiple
sub-32-byte fields that could share a slot), expensive types (mappings
of structs, dynamic arrays), and missing 'immutable'/'constant' on
write-once configuration.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_storage_gas_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze storage variable gas usage

    @Reasoning:
    Analyze storage layout efficiency, identify expensive storage operations,
    suggest packing optimizations, and detect unnecessary storage usage
    that increases gas costs.
    @End Reasoning

    Let state_variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let gas_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let var_names be proc keys from Dict with state_variables
    Let var_count be proc size from List with var_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than var_count:
        Let var_name be proc get from List with var_names, i
        Let state_var be proc get from Dict with state_variables, var_name

        proc analyze_storage_variable_gas with analyzer, var_name, state_var

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads the functions_registry from @48 and gas_warnings list from
@128. Iterates the function names, fetching each function_def. For
each, calls check_function_loop_gas_limits which inspects the
function body for unbounded loops, loops over storage arrays
(SLOAD per iteration is expensive), and deeply nested loops.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_loop_gas_limits" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check for potential gas limit issues in loops

    @Reasoning:
    Identify loops that could hit gas limits, unbounded loops, and
    operations that scale poorly with input size that could cause
    out-of-gas errors in smart contract execution.
    @End Reasoning

    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let gas_warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let function_names be proc keys from Dict with functions_registry
    Let func_count be proc size from List with function_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let function_name be proc get from List with function_names, i
        Let function_def be proc get from Dict with functions_registry, function_name

        proc check_function_loop_gas_limits with analyzer, function_name, function_def

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TYPE VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four sub-passes:
  1. validate_function_signatures - signature consistency
  2. check_type_compatibility - assignment/expression type checking
  3. validate_type_conversions - explicit cast validity
  4. check_abi_encoding_compatibility - external function ABI rules
Each sub-pass owns its own iteration and registers any failures via
add_solidity_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_solidity_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate type compatibility and function signatures

    @Reasoning:
    Validate Solidity type compatibility, function signature consistency,
    type conversions, and ensure proper type usage according to Solidity
    type system specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_function_signatures from analyzer
    proc check_type_compatibility from analyzer
    proc validate_type_conversions from analyzer
    proc check_abi_encoding_compatibility from analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads the function_signatures Dictionary from @96. Lists its keys
(qualified function names like "ContractName.functionName") and
iterates calling validate_individual_function_signature on each. The
inner pass owns the actual signature comparison (parameter type
mismatches, return type mismatches against any override target).
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_function_signatures" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate function signature consistency

    @Reasoning:
    Check function signatures for parameter type compatibility, return type
    consistency, and proper ABI encoding compatibility for external function
    calls and interface implementations.
    @End Reasoning

    Let function_signatures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let sig_names be proc keys from Dict with function_signatures
    Let sig_count be proc size from List with sig_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than sig_count:
        Let func_name be proc get from List with sig_names, i
        Let function_sig be proc get from Dict with function_signatures, func_name

        proc validate_individual_function_signature with analyzer, func_name, function_sig

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Reads the first byte of version_spec. If '^' (94), strips the
caret prefix and calls validate_version_number_format on the
remainder (caret-range "compatible with X.Y.Z"). If '~' (126),
strips the tilde prefix and calls the same checker (tilde-range
"approximate X.Y.Z"). Otherwise treats the input as an exact
version or comparison range and calls validate_version_number_format
on the whole string.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_solidity_version_format" takes analyzer as Integer, version_spec as Integer:
    Note: Validate Solidity version specification format

    @Reasoning:
    Check pragma solidity version specification follows valid format
    (exact, range, caret, tilde), validate version numbers, and ensure
    compatibility with available compiler versions.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check for valid version operators
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with version_spec, 0

    If first_char is equal to 94:  Note: bitwise xor (caret)
        Note: Caret range - compatible version
        Let version_part be proc string_substring from StringCore with version_spec, 1, proc string_length from StringCore with version_spec minus 1
        proc validate_version_number_format with analyzer, version_part
    Otherwise:
        If first_char is equal to 126:  Note: ~ (tilde)
            Note: Tilde range - approximate version
            Set version_part to proc string_substring from StringCore with version_spec, 1, proc string_length from StringCore with version_spec minus 1
            proc validate_version_number_format with analyzer, version_part
        Otherwise:
            Note: Exact version or range
            proc validate_version_number_format with analyzer, version_spec
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates that a version number string has the major.minor.patch
form expected by Solidity's semver. Implemented as a dot-count
check (must contain exactly two dots). Numeric validation of the
individual components is intentionally not performed here - Solidity
permits comparison operators like ^0.8 (no patch) elsewhere in the
range string, so a stricter check would reject valid pragmas.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls count_character_occurrences_in_string with text = version_number
and char = ".". If the count is not exactly 2, builds an "Invalid
version format (expected major.minor.patch): <value>" message and
appends via add_solidity_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_version_number_format" takes analyzer as Integer, version_number as Integer:
    Note: Validate version number format (major.minor.patch)

    Let dot_count be proc count_character_occurrences_in_string with version_number, "."

    If dot_count is not equal to 2:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Invalid version format (expected major.minor.patch): ", version_number
        proc add_solidity_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts how many times a specified character appears in a string.
Used by validate_version_number_format to count the dot separators
in a Solidity version pragma value like "0.8.20" (must contain
exactly two dots for major.minor.patch).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Treats char_to_count as a single-character string and reads its
first byte via string_char_at(.,0) as target_char. Iterates through
text by index, incrementing count each time string_char_at(text,i)
equals target_char. Returns the final count.
@End Implementation
Process called "count_character_occurrences_in_string" takes text as Integer, char_to_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Count occurrences of character in string

    Let count be 0
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with text
    Let target_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with char_to_count, 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than length:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with text, i
        If char is equal to target_char:
            Set count to count plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runs per-state-variable validation: visibility specifier (state
variables can be public/private/internal but not external) and
naming convention check (typically camelCase for non-constants,
SCREAMING_SNAKE for constants).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads var_name, var_type, var_visibility from the parser. Calls
validate_solidity_visibility with element_type = "state variable"
and check_solidity_naming_conventions. The type validation
(checking that var_type is a defined struct/enum/primitive) is done
by a later cross-reference pass against the analyzer's structs and
enums registries.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_state_variable_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, state_var as Integer:
    Note: Validate state variable declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Check state variable has valid type, appropriate visibility, proper
    mutability specification, and follows Solidity state variable
    declaration rules and conventions.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be proc get_solidity_state_variable_name from state_var
    Let var_type be proc get_solidity_state_variable_type from state_var
    Let var_visibility be proc get_solidity_state_variable_visibility from state_var

    Note: Validate visibility modifier
    proc validate_solidity_visibility with analyzer, var_visibility, "state variable"

    Note: Check naming conventions
    proc check_solidity_naming_conventions with analyzer, var_name, "state variable"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runs the per-function validation suite: visibility, state mutability,
and special-function naming rules (constructor, receive, fallback
have specific syntactic requirements). The body-level analyses
(reentrancy, overflow, access control) run from analyze_solidity_security
later in the pipeline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads func_name, func_visibility, func_mutability via the parser's
get_solidity_function_* accessors. Calls
validate_solidity_visibility (with "function" as element type),
then validate_solidity_state_mutability, then
validate_special_function_rules for handling the constructor/
receive/fallback edge cases.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_function_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, contract_name as Integer, function_def as Integer:
    Note: Validate function declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Check function has valid signature, appropriate visibility, proper
    state mutability, and follows Solidity function declaration rules
    and security best practices.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be proc get_solidity_function_name from function_def
    Let func_visibility be proc get_solidity_function_visibility from function_def
    Let func_mutability be proc get_solidity_function_state_mutability from function_def

    Note: Validate visibility modifier
    proc validate_solidity_visibility with analyzer, func_visibility, "function"

    Note: Validate state mutability
    proc validate_solidity_state_mutability with analyzer, func_mutability

    Note: Check special function names (constructor, receive, fallback)
    proc validate_special_function_rules with analyzer, func_name, function_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a visibility specifier against Solidity's allowed set
{public, private, internal, external}. The element_type parameter
(e.g. "state variable", "function") is interpolated into the error
message but does not narrow the allowed set here - element-specific
restrictions (state variables can't be external; constructors can't
be private) are checked by separate passes that have richer
context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a List of the four valid visibility strings. Iterates,
calling string_equals against the input. If no match, builds an
"Invalid visibility for <element_type>: <visibility>" message and
adds it via add_solidity_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_solidity_visibility" takes analyzer as Integer, visibility as Integer, element_type as Integer:
    Note: Validate Solidity visibility modifier

    @Reasoning:
    Check visibility modifier is valid for the element type and follows
    Solidity visibility rules. Different elements (functions, state variables)
    have different allowed visibility modifiers.
    @End Reasoning

    Let valid_visibilities be proc create from List
    proc add from List with valid_visibilities, "public"
    proc add from List with valid_visibilities, "private"
    proc add from List with valid_visibilities, "internal"
    proc add from List with valid_visibilities, "external"

    Let visibility_count be proc size from List with valid_visibilities
    Let is_valid be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than visibility_count:
        Let valid_visibility be proc get from List with valid_visibilities, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with visibility, valid_visibility
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Set is_valid to 1
            Break
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Invalid visibility for ", element_type
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, ": "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringCore with error, visibility
        proc add_solidity_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a function's state-mutability declaration against the
Solidity-allowed set {pure, view, payable, nonpayable}. The set is
position-independent (any of the four is valid for any function in
isolation) so this check is a simple membership test; cross-field
consistency (e.g. pure functions touching storage) is done by a
separate pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a List of the four valid mutability strings. Iterates with
string_equals against the input. If no match, appends an
"Invalid state mutability: <value>" message via
add_solidity_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_solidity_state_mutability" takes analyzer as Integer, mutability as Integer:
    Note: Validate Solidity state mutability modifier

    @Reasoning:
    Check state mutability modifier is valid and appropriate for function
    type. Functions can be pure, view, payable, or nonpayable with specific
    restrictions on state access.
    @End Reasoning

    Let valid_mutabilities be proc create from List
    proc add from List with valid_mutabilities, "pure"
    proc add from List with valid_mutabilities, "view"
    proc add from List with valid_mutabilities, "payable"
    proc add from List with valid_mutabilities, "nonpayable"

    Let mutability_count be proc size from List with valid_mutabilities
    Let is_valid be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than mutability_count:
        Let valid_mutability be proc get from List with valid_mutabilities, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with mutability, valid_mutability
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Set is_valid to 1
            Break
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Invalid state mutability: ", mutability
        proc add_solidity_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records a fatal semantic error and flips the has_error flag. Used
when the analyzer hits a condition that should stop the pipeline
(null AST input, malformed input, internal invariant violation).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes error_message pointer to analyzer @192 and writes 1 to
analyzer @200 (the has_error flag). analyze_solidity_contract
checks @200 at the end and returns 0 if set.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_solidity_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a message to validation_errors. Unlike
set_solidity_semantic_error, this does NOT flip the has_error flag -
it accumulates a non-fatal error that the analyzer will report
alongside others at the end. set_solidity_semantic_error is
reserved for fatal cases that should abort the pipeline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_errors @160 and calls List.add to push the message
pointer onto the list.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_solidity_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160
    proc add from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a message to validation_warnings. Warnings are non-fatal -
they do NOT flip has_error and the analysis continues to completion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_warnings @168 and calls List.add. Used by passes
that detect quality issues but want to allow the contract to
proceed to later phases.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_solidity_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168
    proc add from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a message to the security_issues List. Used by general
security analysis passes when an issue doesn't fit the more
specific reentrancy/overflow/access-control buckets.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads security_issues @120 and calls List.add to push the message
pointer onto the list. No null-guard on the list because it is
guaranteed populated by create_solidity_semantic_analyzer.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_solidity_security_issue" takes analyzer as Integer, issue_message as Integer:
    Note: Add security issue to security issues list

    Let security_issues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    proc add from List with security_issues, issue_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
External one-call entry point. Creates an analyzer, runs the full
analysis pipeline against the given AST, and returns the analyzer
so the caller can interrogate it via the get_* accessors. The
return is the analyzer pointer regardless of analysis success - the
caller uses solidity_semantic_has_errors to check status.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_solidity_semantic_analyzer. If allocation failed (0
returned), returns 0. Otherwise calls analyze_solidity_contract
(its return value is captured into result but not propagated
because the analyzer itself is what callers need). Returns the
analyzer pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "solidity_semantic_analyze" takes solidity_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on Solidity AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_solidity_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_solidity_contract with analyzer, solidity_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

